    * For solopreneur product track: /start → /ceo-job → /cpo-define/scope/requirements → /cto-stack/ai/mvp (7 commands from idea to PRD and build plan). [2]
* Routing and user experience layer
    * @Anennya identified need for routing that stitches commands together so users invoke them via plain English, not explicit slash commands. [27:35]
    * @Anennya proposed Claude should infer which commands to trigger based on conversational input (e.g., "I don't know the right price" → pricing command). [28:45]
    * @Patty OBrien Novak emphasized the system must guide users on what comes next without requiring them to manually navigate 40+ commands. [36:18]
    * @Aparna Ramesh noted shared memory file should persist context (business details, niche, pricing) across commands so each doesn't repeat itself. [30:50]
* Target audience definition
    * Claude identified three primary audiences: domain experts building products, structured thinkers starting businesses, and Build TogetHER members comfortable with AI tools but lacking business frameworks. [1:00:05]
    * Tool will not serve true beginners, experienced PMs/developers (who already know frameworks), or people seeking advice rather than structured process. [1:00:05]
    * @Anennya and @Patty OBrien Novak agreed the toolkit should target domain experts and structured thinkers needing scaffolding, not execution advice. [1:00:37]
* Shared memory and connective tissue
    * @Aparna Ramesh proposed shared business brief that commands read from and write to, reducing repetition and enabling downstream commands to inherit context. [30:50]
    * @Patty OBrien Novak volunteered to explore shared memory implementation, noting prior experience with similar patterns on other projects. [1:13:39]
    * Shared brief unlocks efficiency: once populated, remaining commands become cheaper to build since they inherit context instead of re-asking users. [1]
